Changes looks good. This commit depends on the backend networkd change https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-networkd/+/63124. Until that is merged, this may break the DHCP patch.
Thank you Ed.
Thank you Ed
Still waiting on https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-networkd/+/63124
Please change these variables to "dnsV4Enabled" to differentiate from v6.
Done
NTP is a global setting, outside of DHCP.  Why are we enabling NTP on a DHCP V4/V6 basis?
I think this setting is to indicate whether the interface uses DHCPv4/DHCPv6 supplied NTP servers.

Yes. Dynamic NTP servers will be assigned onto the interface based on this flag. 

If v4 is enabled, the DHCPv4 server supplied NTP servers will be applied, and If v6 is enabled, the IPv6 router -or- DHCPv6 server supplied NTP servers will be applied.
PS: Both can co-exist on a single interface.
And......  How did you verify that the NTP servers were accepted correctly?  Did you read back the NTP settings on an NTP DHCP enabled network?
And did you observe the time getting set properly?

We've tested only the SET and GET on this property for this commit.
Since fetching the time etc are in the scope of the time manager & network we did not test that here
Please test the feature as a user would.
Been a couple of weeks, have you had a chance to test?
Ping again.  Had a chance to test?
We checked with our test team on this. Looks like we have tested it by mocking the NTP server due to unavailability of a local NTP server and its behaving as expected

> Looks like we have tested it by mocking the NTP server due to unavailability of a local NTP server and its behaving as expected

What does "mocking an NTP server" mean?  Not actually testing with an actual NTP/DHCP server doesn't seem like enough.  Why do you have confidence that this code is correct if it hasn't been tried?  Can we get more testing here?
Let me check with our test team on this. I'll try to include them into this conversation for their observations
Looking for a reply here

you posted a systemd config which isn't really helpful.  The test I would expect would be to set an NTP server, and ensure that the BMC gets the correct time.

> Timed out waiting for reply from 10.5.5.30:123 (10.5.5.30).

This log implies that something isn't working in the implementation.

> The test I would expect would be to set an NTP server and ensure that the BMC gets the correct time.

Is this test required for the changes done at this commit? Per my view, when the NTPEnabled property is enabled, then setting & getting the NTP server IP on the interface as per the network type mentioned is good enough. Syncing the BMC time with the NTP server is out of this commit scope.

This is making changes to a user-facing API.  SOMEONE needs to test that the user facing API does the expected thing, just as was required when this feature was first checked in.  Whether it's tested as part of this commit, or the phoshpor-networkd commit, I expect that testing done, yes.  If that testing isn't done, how do you have confidence that it worked?  Looking at the config files by hand doesn't tell you whether or not the config files are correctly written.

I would also mention that TESTING.md is where we document the process and expectations for testing, if you disagree with the current set of policies, that's fine, I'm happy to have that discussion, but it needs to be had outside of a single patch.  Re-discussing appropriate testing every commit wastes maintainers time.

The error is expected as NTP server was unreachable, NTP server detail is sent from DHCP server, BMC is extracting it & sending time request. Since NTP server is down it is throwing timeout error which is expected.

> Since NTP server is down it is throwing timeout error which is expected.

Right, so we need to get a test setup with an NTP server available.

I see no mention of compatibility impact here with existing clients.  Is there any?

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/DEVELOPING.md#compatibility
Please actually answer this, even if the answer is "I'm looking into it"

I had requested @Johnathan for his inputs on the impact on IPMI in the networkd commit, but couldn't get any.

https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-networkd/+/63124/comments/06e2b078_7344203d

The question was not about IPMI impact.  That's not of importance to this review.  What's important is that if there are users that previously set DHCP, and expected both dhcp v4 and dhcp v6 to be set, because that was the old behavior.
